@node "Install_BBS" "Regular BBS operation"
@next "Install_FTN"
@prev "Installation"
@{fg shine}Regular BBS operation@{fg text}

 Best, copy the whole damn thing to pfiles:1oo/clog/ ("1oo" is a
 motherdir since we also made some other pretty tools that should
 reside in there to keep your overloaded pfiles dir a bit tidier).


Change BBSText @{b}line 99@{ub} to (nifty method that is btw!):

 \\n1Logging... {#0pfiles:1oo/clog/1oo_clog.rexx}OK.\\n1@Logoff complete.


Change BBSText @{b}line 934@{ub} to:

 {#0pfiles:1oo/clog/1oo_clog.chat}\\n1Now entering chatmode with %s


(as usual, "\\"=CTRL-Y and "{"=CTRL-Q)
@endnode

@node "Install_FTN" "FTN session logging"
@next "Configuration"
@prev "Installation"
@{fg shine}FTN session logging@{fg text}

 This section is a bit tricky so I'll explain a bit more lengthy.

 If you want to log netcall sessions with your frontend (Trapdoor,
 Gotcha, GMS or any other that supply %-commands within an
 "AfterSession" command), call C/Log like this from the mailer's
 aftersession command or your aftersession script:

    @{b}RX <path>/1oo_CLog.rexx NET <baudrate> <port#> <all addresses>@{ub}

 The keywords must be exactly in this order as the method I use to
 fiddle around with any # of aka's you might pass to the script is not
 exactly AmigaDOS ReadArgs() style :) - I didn't want to make my
 script dependant on rexxdossupport.library, nor include a 5kB ARexx
 part to it...

Keywords are:

    @{b}<baudrate>@{ub}       the modem<>modem connect rate

    @{b}<port#>@{ub}          the bbs-portnumber that represents the frontend's
                     line.

    @{b}<all addresses>@{ub}  the list of ALL aka's of the calling system. Make
                     sure you have a correctly compiled nodelist for at
                     least ONE of those addresses, or you'll have some
                     garbage in your datafile. Its not important if the
                     addresses are 4D or 5D, my program will strip the
                     5D part of the address(es) because GetNode only
                     handles 4D addresses, anyway.


 For @{b}Gotcha!@{ub} on line 1 of your system, the commandline would be:

    @{b}RX <path>/1oo_CLog.rexx NET %B 1 %n %A@{ub}


 However, if you have an aftersession script that also starts your
 tosser, ticker, or whatever else, use it like this (given path's are
 just examples):

    @{b}Execute Mail:Batch/Aftersession.bat %B 1 "%n %A"@{ub}

 The quotemarks around the %n (main address of the calling system) and
 the %A (list of all aka's of the calling system) are necessary in this
 case! Be careful with the AfterSession command of your mailer,
 you might have to "escape" the quotemarks with backslashes. In my
 @{b}Gotcha.config@{ub} file, it looks like this:

    @{b}AFTERSESSION="Execute Mail:Batch/Aftersession.bat %B 1 \\"%n %A\\""@{ub}

 The script itself might look like this:

    .key baud,node,akalist
    .bra {
    .ket }

    RX PFiles:1oo/CLog/1oo_CLog.rexx NET {baud} {node} {akalist}
    CNet:Toss


 Please note that the "GETNODE" command from the TrapDoor distribution
 requires a nodelist compiled with TRAPLIST! I haven't tested this with
 any other mailer, but it should work fine since almost anyone
 will have a traplist compiled nodelist & the getnode utility.

 If you can't get it running with your mailer, send email and I'll try
 to help.
@endnode

