@node "CFG_Online" "Online configuration"
@next "CFG_Cookies"
@prev "Configuration"

 @{fg shine}Online Configuration@{fg text}

 C/Log has a built in configuration editor. When @{"viewing the log" link "Viewing" 0}, press
 "C" to enter it. Here's an overview of what the items will do - the
 same text is displayed when you select an item from within
 the program.


 @{b}(1) Maximum loglines@{ub}

 This value holds the number of overall calls that will be in the log.
 Setting it to 10 will result in the traditional "last ten calls"
 style. Note: the number you enter here has mostly nothing to do with
 the number of lines a caller will see, as this depends on his/her
 termheight.


 @{b}(2) Newday divider@{ub}

 This switch en- or disables the adding of the "a new day..." divider
 when the maint part runs. If you have only very few calls/day, it
 might look better if you turn it off. :)


 @{b}(3) Show xfer relation@{ub}

 Here you can select if you wish to show a users transfer relation
 in the log by handle colors. An "elite" users ratio must be below the
 limit you set, and his/her handle will appear yellow in the log.
 A leechers ratio must be above the second limit you set, and its
 handle color will appear in red in the log.


 @{b}(4) Count relogins@{ub}

 This setting allows you to alter the counting of calls/day when a user
 does a re-login. Turning it off will NOT increase the calls/day value,
 turning it on will increase the value on every re-login. The third and
 best option will add re-logins only to the calls/day value if the
 re-login is done under a different handle than the previous call was.


 @{b}(5) Log local calls@{ub}

 This option lets you decide whether you want to add local calls to the
 log or not, say if you are visited by a friend and he logs on to your
 BBS from the console.


 @{b}(6) Log sysop calls from remote@{ub}

 If the sysop calls in from remote (via nullmodem etc.) for testing
 purposes, it might not be wanted to add these calls to the log.


 @{b}(7) Path & name of GETNODE@{ub}

 To @{"log netcalls" link "Install_FTN" 0}, C/Log pulls some data from the GETNODE utility of the
 TrapDoor distribution. To use GETNODE, C/Log needs to know the path
 and name of the program (usually Mail:Bin/GetNode or something similar).
 If you leave this line empty, no netcalls will be logged, even if you have
 installed C/Log in the AfterSession part of your mailer.


 @{b}(8) List of Zones for Netcall logging@{ub}

 C/Log can only pull information from a node via GETNODE if you have a
 traplist compiled nodelist for the corresponding net. Here you can
 specify which zones (XX: part of the nodenumber) can be processed.
 Separate multiple entries with spaces. If you have a compiled fidonet
 nodelist and want to log callers from all zones, the appropriate entry
 would be "1 2 3 4 5 6".
@endnode

@node "CFG_Cookies" "Cookies"
@next "CFG_Logos"
@prev "Configuration"

 @{fg shine}Cookies@{fg text}

 "Cookies" are the singleline words of wisdom often seen in signatures
 or origins. C/Log will display a randomly selected cookie out of the
 1oo_clog.cookie file when viewing the last callers log. If the file
 does not exist it will show some version information.

 To change/add cookies, look at the supplied cookie file and you get
 the idea. The FIRST line contains the number of cookies (to make access
 as fast as possible in ARexx, look at the routine), the taglines
 should be no longer than 74 chars each (and of course only single
 lines!).
@endnode

@node "CFG_Logos" "Logos"
@next "History"
@prev "Configuration"

 @{fg shine}Selfmade Logos@{fg text}

 If you want to include your own logos, just keep the following in
 mind, as C/Log calculates the length of the logo itself: don't add
 screenclear in the beginning (CTRL-L or \\f1 or ESC[2JESC[H sequence),
 and complete each line with a single linefeed ($0a).

 In the archive you should find logos for Ascii (sys/tt0), Amiga (tt3)
 and IBM (tt2) terminals. If you want to add C/G graphics (tt1) and
 SkyPix (tt4), you should really do them yourself! :)

 Some background:

 @{b}ASCII@{ub}    only covers chars in the range of decimal 32-127

 @{b}AMIGA@{ub}    uses @{fg fill}8 colors@{fg text} and an ISO charset

 @{b}IBM@{ub}      uses @{fg fill}16 colors@{fg text} and an IBMGFX charset
@endnode

@node "History" "History"
@next "Contact"
@prev "Configuration"

 @{fg shine}History@{fg text}

 1.0     Initial version by Red Hawk of Interactive

 1.1     Fixed version by Neurodancer/at-that-time ABYSS
         - fixed some bugs (forgotten quotemarks etc.)
         - shows up/downbytes per CALL (not per DAY... yuk!)
         - local calls will be entirely filtered
         - sysop calls will be entirely filtered (even if remote)
         - shows organisation instead of location
         - tuned output for 16 colors
         - auto adapts to users terminal height
         - fixed logo removed, can be any logo now

 1.2     [internal]
         - time in 24h format now
         - optional tagline for new day (done by Dreamer)

 1.3     [internal]
         - shows carrier loss (logofftype variable)
         - shows 24h time now correct (24:13 was quite crappy!)
         - shows chativity of users with external module

 Name changed to "1oo% Callerslog"

 Dreamer & me founded "1oo%", Aerosoul joined, Dreamer left Shoot,
 joined Supplex, conspirative 1oo% meetings at my flat, very productive
 that was indeed! Wait for more to come!

 1.4     - logs more actions
         - easier way of making time 24h format (by Fate)
         - counts daily calls (and shows yesterdays upon this data)
         - viewer autodetects logo height, so the logo size can be anything
           now without problems with the automatic "fullsizing".
         - ONE external config file
         - now shows today/total/ydays calls + total up/down files/bytes
         - uses maximum available lines again
         - changed outfit & design a bit
         - views baudrate as e.g. 33k6 (USR rules! :)
         - numerous other little enhancements.

 1.5     [internal]
         - logs daily calls AND transfers (the totals were crap, eh?)
         - thanks to the usual getuser, it knows where it is stored
           and searches this path for config, datafiles etc.

 1.6     [internal]
         - re-worked the code a bit here and there

 1.7     [internal]
         - Maintenance part added by Mxlprx

 1.8     [internal]
         - re-worked the 24h time again. Fate's method does reset the
           the time if the call begun before and ended AFTER midnite so
           it would always show 00:00 as login time (NOTE: I just found
           out this is a bug in CNet, not in Fate's nor my routine!)
         - logs all-time-highest record calls/uploads/downloads
         - logs messages today/yesterday/records
         - name changed to "C/Log" (no more name changes, please! :)
         - merged datafile updater, viewer and maint part into one
         - threw out maintenance part by Mxlprx, due to the changed
           format of the .stat file it wouldn't work anymore
         - cosmetical changes (more support for splitting ibm/iso)
         - uncovers superb uploaders and extreme leechers by the
           color of the handle in the log: normal=cyan, leech=red,
           elite=yellow (sysop can switch this feature on/off and
           define the limits)

 1.9     [internal]
         - changes some outfit (bit of 'elite' stylism, I like it)
         - added cookies (taglines)
         - displays users organisation, if none is set uses the location

  ** ATTENTION! OLD DATAFILES DON'T WORK ANYMORE! ***

 2.0     - rewrote the read/save datafile part, everything except the
           actions is stored without colors & empty spaces now; colors
           are then set according to the callers terminal type (8/16)

         - you have noticed that the names (and home directory) have
           changed from 1oo_last#? to 1oo_clog#?, this has been done to
           avoid conflicts due to the changed datafile structure; if you
           are using an older version, don't forget to change all links
           to C/Log to the new names (BBSText, GFiles, sys.welcome...)

         - wrote a converter for your old pre-2.0 datafiles; thanks to
           Count Dan for uncovering some problems.

         - fixed a problem in the maint part thanks to Devil.

 2.1     [internal]
         - when a user made a post to a subboard, the actions showed that
           he also sent mail, I mixed up some vars. Fixed thanks to Devil.

         - wrote a primitive (CNet "EP" style :-) configuration part.
           Sysops press "C" when viewing the log, or call the program with
           the "CONFIG" keyword (from PFiles or whereever) to enter the
           config editor. I think I made every possible sanity check for
           the crap you enter there... :)

         - more configurability added, you can now decide whether to log
           local calls, sysop calls and relogins or not. Additionally,
           operation on re-login can be set to log only if the handle
           after re-login is different. Just start the config part and
           you'll see, every item is explained in short when invoking it.

         - added logging of netcalls

         - a maintenance event is no longer needed. The date of the last
           run is saved in the stats file, if they differ, the program
           will do the maint stuff

         - re-worked netcall logging, now processing all aka's to find
           a matching zone for logging

         - expanded today/yesterday/record byte transfer space in the
           viewer module to allow a max. of 999999 kbytes, as there are
           bbs out there which broke the old limit (hey Ben! :)

 2.2     - re-worked the rating (elite/normal/leecher) routine to consider
           both bytes *and* files. You can leave your old limits untouched
           since the resulting value is in the same range, yet the results
           will be more accurate for e.g. a user who uploaded 2mb in 10
           files compared to another user who uploaded 2mb in 1 file as
           the one with 10 files obviously contributed more to the bbs.

         - added carriercheck in front of the view part, since most of the
           time carrier loss happens right after a (bad) connect, so in
           this case C/Log, which is mostly shown during logon, immediately
           exits.

         - if sysop logs off with normal "Off" command and sysop logging
           is off, a prompt defaulting to "no" appears, asking the sysop
           if he wants to log his call anyway - no logging & no prompt
           if an instant logoff "Off!" is performed. This was requested
           by Devil and I think its a nice idea. The prompt will count
           down from 9 to 0, then quit with "NO" as default answer.
           
         - if the handle is empty, C/Log immediately exits. It happened
           to Devil that everytime he turned on his other, nullmodem
           connected computer, that CNet somehow thought there was a
           call. This might affect other sysops out there too, dunno?
@endnode

